    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-09-26T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-09-26T04:00:00-05:00" n="537"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d537">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/1397: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-09-26T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 26, 1935—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:08 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>376. May 221, June 21, 11 a.m. The Secretary-General has circulated the text of a
                    telegram addressed to him yesterday by the Emperor of Abyssinia, of which the
                    main points are the following: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>The telegram begins: “We ask you to submit the following to the Council”.
                            It then states that in order that there might be no doubt as to the
                            aggression in case of hostilities, the Abyssinian troops were several
                            months ago withdrawn 30 kilometers from the frontier. Reference is made
                            to Abyssinia’s “previously informed [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>] request
                            for the despatch of impartial observers to establish the facts in regard
                            to any aggression or other incident that might occur in order to fix the
                            responsibility therefor.” In conclusion, the Emperor asks “that the
                            Council should take any other precautions it may think advisable”
                            (Consulate’s 375, September 26 [<hi rend="italic">25</hi>], 6 p.m., 6th
                                paragraph<note n="84" xml:id="d537fn84">Not printed.</note>).</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The British inform me that this communication was sent at their suggestion as
                    indirectly strengthening the Abyssinian position but that it is not designed
                    that the Council take action thereon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
